SIMPLE: intrigue
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Intrigue
<hw>In*trigue"</hw> <pr>(⟦icr⟧n*tr⟦emac⟧g")</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Intrigued</conjf>
<pr>(-tr⟦emac⟧gd")</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Intriguing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>intriguer</ets>, OF.
<ets>intriquer</ets>, <ets>entriquer</ets>; cf. It.
<ets>intrigare</ets>. See <er>Intricate</er>, <er>Extricate</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To form a plot or scheme; to contrive to accomplish a
purpose by secret artifice.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To carry on a secret and illicit love or
amour.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Intrigue</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Intrigue
<hw>In*trigue"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To fill with artifice and
duplicity; to complicate; to embarrass.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How doth it [sin] perplex and <qex>intrique</qex> the whole course
of your lives!</q> <rj><qau>Dr. J. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Intrigue</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Intrigue
<hw>In*trigue"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>intrique</ets>. See
<er>Intrigue</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Intricacy; complication.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Sir M. Hale.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A complicated plot or scheme intended to effect some
purpose by secret artifice; conspiracy; stratagem.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Busy meddlers with <qex>intrigues</qex> of state.</q>
<rj><qau>Pomfret.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The plot of a play or romance; a complicated scheme
of designs, actions, and events.</def> <rj><au>Pope.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A secret and illicit love affair between two persons
of different sexes; an amour; a liaison.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The hero of a comedy is represented victorious in all his
<qex>intrigues</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Plot; scheme; conspiracy; machination.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Intriguer</ent>⟦br⟧
